@@eThe Kinetimancer Tradition@@N

@@yThe Kinetic Formulists@@N
The Kinetimancer synthesis arose from the work of the Kinetic Formulists, an
independent scholarly order that studied the mathematical structure of force
transmission across different domains of reality. They documented a structural
analogy: the equations describing how will-imposition propagates through cognitive
architecture were mathematically analogous to those describing how entropic force
propagates through biological systems undergoing dissolution. Both traditions, the
Entropy Scholars and the Egomancer lineage, were working with momentum, one
redirecting the momentum of decay and the other redirecting the momentum of
imposed intent.

@@yThe Violet Compact Classification@@N
When the Formulists' manuscripts came to the attention of the Violet Compact's
registry scholars, they classified the convergence as dangerous theoretical
synthesis and logged its practitioners under a new term: Kinetimancer. The
bureaucratic label became the tradition's name, carried forward by practitioners
who found the Compact's unease to be confirmation enough. The enhanced monitoring
designation exists in registry records as an unfulfilled administrative intention,
as the tradition's practitioners have always been too few, too independent, and too
technically sophisticated for generalist scholars to assess.

@@yThe Momentum Doctrine@@N
The tradition's theoretical foundation holds that all effective force operates
through the redirection of momentum. Rather than generating force from nothing, the
practitioner identifies existing force vectors and redirects them. An opponent's
attack contains momentum that can be turned to amplify the practitioner's own
effects. Environmental processes contain momentum that can be redirected without
the practitioner needing to generate equivalent force. In the cognitive domain, an
opponent's intense concentration can be redirected or disrupted more efficiently
than it can be directly overwritten.

@@yKinetic Reversion@@N
The tradition's signature technique takes incoming force and reverses its momentum
vector, returning it toward its origin. Practitioners who have mastered it describe
a fundamental change in their relationship to combat: every incoming attack becomes
a potential resource. The more powerful the attack, the more momentum available for
redirection. This inverts the normal logic by which more powerful attacks are more
threatening; for a Kinetimancer, they are more useful.
